author: @amrutaj28
comment:
Samdhish I have some constructive criticism which I hope you'll take well. I seriously didn't like the way you did the following.
1. Laughed at many serious things Imran spoke about with vulnerability. It was very inappropriate, disrespectful and just... didn't make sense to laugh there. Nothing was funny in those points. Like when he spoke about the fan of Mere Brother Ki Dulhan.
2. Interrupted him sooo much and kept looking here and there when he was giving a properly detailed answer. If you don't have enough attention span or focus, please don't interview people like this who have so much depth to offer. It's very rude.
3. Just because Imran is super polite, doesn't mean you judge him directly and ask about how he hasn't spoken a sentence of Hindi. He's already told u about his upbringing. U could have asked the same question in a different way and tone instead of sounding so judgy. Like "I noticed you don't speak much Hindi, is there a reason for that?". Not like - "Man u haven't spoken a single sentence of Hindi! What is this??"

There's a lot more u did wrong but please consider this feedback so that you can get more such good people on ur platform. Otherwise this will really bring ur image down and guests won't be comfortable.

author: @ecp9782
comment:
A popular saying says "a prophet is never accepted in his own town and by his own people"; Or a saying in Hindi "Ghar ka murgi dal barabar".

Therefore it would be wiser on the part of the Meghalaya CM to ignore all his political adversaries and steer ahead to do what is best before his conscience for public interest and for Meghalaya to reap good fruits in the years to come.

Those who find the Meghalaya CM as useless are people who choose to ignore all the past CMs and their functions 
and 
mind you; they were over 27 CMs in Meghalaya and there were all together 17 individuals who had become Meghalaya CMs till date.
Some of the 17 had been gracious to their office as CMs and the current Meghalaya CM is among the some of them.

Unfortunately it is a historical fact that the critics chose to brush aside. Nonetheless a historical truth is before us to weigh after we cease to be biased to facts.

The MDA 1&2 government in Meghalaya have done commendable works in many spheres though there are still prospects for further works; 
Yet those who shun to acknowledge the works choose to link all works of the government to debts, which to me is quite not the case to say the least.

author: @isamsharma
comment:
I was smiling throughout this interview, so much so that I didnâ€™t want it to end. I wanted more questions around his thought process and approach to film making and why does he not already have an academy. Samdish does make an interviewee crawl out of comfort zones so unsure why folks are alarmed. Iâ€™d have asked so many more questions though :) 
I remember noticing (read discovering) Farhan Akhtar and being remotely interested in finding out about the director of a film, when I watched Lakshya for the first time. My father was in the army then and we watched it in CME, Pune. For me, there was so much resonance with a movie (I was barely a teenager) like the characters, their intentions, the innocence, integrity, and of course SEL songs. The dialogues, the simple yet impactful and realistic scenes, the no-nonsense, the non-climactic and unhyped progress of the story, the non-misogynistic jokes that were hilarious. I still remember some dialogues (Malliahbad ke aam). All of the characters had such depth and were way ahead of that time. I could go on and on tbh. And all of his movies that followed.â¤
This man also has my utmost respect for not just believing in feminism now but since the 2000s when no one else really did or atleast appeared to. 
People appreciate this father-son duo now, Iâ€™ve been a fan since 2004. ğŸ¥¹

author: @hummingbird2309
comment:
Sorry for being overly critical, but this interview was a mess.

Samdish was all over the place, lacking insightful questions and interrupting Faran incessantly and not letting him finish - which was painful to watch. Only to be interrupted by another tangential question. 

I love the quirky nature of questions Samdish usually comes up with, but this one was just a barrage of very random unrelated questions - and very superficial questions at that. In some of the previous interviews Samdish's non conventional random questions led to a deeper understanding of the people he would interview, but it led to disappointment in this one with FA. Samdish was unable to go deeper with FA and could only scratch the surface. Maybe I'm more disappointed with this interview because I was expecting to be completely dazzled from the start by the conversation with FA and Samdish. 

I was also hoping that Samdish would course correct midway and pay some attention to Farhan's body language - (that he was getting uncomfortable and using his hands to cover his mouth - in a way guarding his responses). FA was very kind, wise and a sport to understand his inteviewer and kept playing with Samdish and returning his volleys with lots of enthusiasm, humor and grace. 
I guess I did come to learn about a deeper/unknown side of someone I've admired/revered since a very long time!

1980s k baad kaafi progress hua hai tharu community me, bahut mehnati hote hain aur bahut mehnat kiye hain ye log.

2005 k around IITs aur AIPMT (Now NEET) me rarely selection hota tha kisi ka.

author: @earth.buddy09
comment:
Samdish bro seems to be excited about caste classification within tharu community. Let me help you bro. Tharu is community in which number of caste/group exist. They mainly reside in terai region of Nepal and India( UK, UP, Bihar). Because of regional identity i. e terai surrounded by forest they are called tharu. UK tharu community is dominated by à¤°à¤¾à¤£à¤¾ tharu (but have other minority tharu too like girnama jugiya, dangra, Rawat, khunka, ). And only à¤°à¤¾à¤£à¤¾ tharu claim they are sishodiya rajput descendent of Maharana Pratap.And uttarakhand à¤°à¤¾à¤£à¤¾ tharu belong to barah(12) Rana clan. When we talk about UP tharu we see mix of tharu group/caste like Chaudhry, Rana, Dhangra, etc. In bihar we see multiple of caste of tharu luke mahato, das, etc. Earlier they were called by there caste / group name but after government affirmative action these caste/group got documented as tharu. But they all are different. Coming to Nepal tharu in south western terai of Nepal we found à¤°à¤¾à¤¨à¤¾ tharu, central nepal terai chaudhry tharu, dang region of nepal terai we found dangora tharu abd south eastern nepal terai we find other tharu. 
Uttarakhand tharu is different in custom and tradition, lanuage. Similar other tharu of UP, Bihar, Nepal tharu are different in custom and tradition and in lanuage.

author: @siwotter
comment: Something to note in the response of the two kids- Aman Kumar was critical of the society around him and some of the culture of bihar. He put forth some beautiful points. But when asked about the birhu tola community he was dismissive of them and said that since the parents are illiterate their children aren't going to school. And you could see he held some negative emotions towards them. Meanwhile Suman Kumar, starts with prideful statements about bihar and its people. He refuses to acknowledge any issues in the society. But when asked about the birhu tola community he has the same positive sentiments towards them and tries to talk about the good side that they are going to school but some teachers aren't teaching. Neither is right or wrong but it's such an interesting yin and yang situation. One is extremely pessimistic and one is hopelessly optimistic.

author: @castmediaok
comment:
The idea of sitting on a couch, sipping a cup of coffee and suddenly a drop spills onto your lavish, expensive sofa; so you simply open an app, book a cleaning slot and there you go, a gig worker is on its way. This moment feels so seamless and privileged that the person using the app feels a sense of power, unknowingly.

But what if the person who shows up at your doorstep had their own story? What if you went to his home and experienced what he goes through in his personal life? Now that is what you call Bharat Ek Khoj.

For this episode, Samdish visited the home of an Urban Company worker, Jitendra Kumar. Presenting: Indiaâ€™s Gig Worker Speaks His Heart Out to Samdish

author: @DhhdDhdhd-w5i
comment:
It's basically a fucked up situation, where both the SC and the protestors are giving their extreme opinions. Actually, many people denying that dog bite is not a problem, are foolish. You can ask yourself, are stray dogs and humans meant to live together?. Don't they listen the number of dog deaths and dog injuries by road accidents? 
The decision taken by the court is also too harsh and the government and the MCD should take  responsibility, and remove these stray dogs from the roads. But this isn't possible as everyone of us know, that how will the dogs be taken after they will be removed. 
The protestors show their animal love, and plead to show humanity, it's kind of ironical to feed chicken to a dog, and most of them are using leather bags and sandals. 
And it's bitter but true, human life is much important dog lives.

author: @power8676
comment: Poor Bihar shares more GDP than Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh, and Assam, and is equal to Odisha, despite these states being rich in minerals and having lower populations, and also these states and top GDP states have more crime than Bihar, as per population.ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ Bihar provides cheap and hard-working laborers for the development of India. Minerals of Bihar were looted when Jharkhand was part of Bihar by the freight equalization policy of 1952, which was implemented by India until 1993, to the detriment of Bihar's development. Then, Lalu Gunjal Raaj came into power, and subsequently, Bihar was looted. Still, Bihar came in 14th in GDP and has a high growth rate, and now, Bihar is not using its overpopulation and cheap and hard-working labourers in the development of Bihar by setting up industries and investing in Bihar. If Bihar uses its hard-working labourers for the development of Bihar, it will come under the top 5 in GDP. If Bihar is developed, then other states will cry due to cheap labour, especially industries in other states. They exploit us(Bihari) through low salaries, long work shifts, and also do racism against Biharis, etc. They abuse us to work there instead of taking advantage of us to develop states (They have a dual face), and sometimes we do not feel safe in other states.

author: @BhaskarBhushanBhaiyaTripleB
comment:
Just for the subaltern perspective- Please please do this more, if you can. 
Only the people who have seen our past and are in the present will have to be gently nudged and asked for a world that we haven't seen.Then only people of today would see and believe that truth isn't monolithic and that what was perhaps just a small part of their life has gained prominence now and as with everything, it is trying to gain strength further and that everything is a cycle of time and that there's no left and right but a centre for everything, around which everything revolves and evolves.And that will be one of the many greatest services to the cause of democracy of this country,for it will keep symbols and names alive. 
I just want that if there's a binary as it has turned out to be- let both sides be as strong as possible and the last two interviews of the nonagenarian veterans puts my faith on the system of people that breeds trust in the civilization values that go beyond the binaries of politics and cultural or economic trends, or beyond the trends of perspective - based time frames. 
Hope you see this and do more of this with people from every field of life and profession.

comment:
Itâ€™s always heartwarming to hear stories from that time. My grandfather, along with his family and cousins, migrated from Delhi to Lahore and eventually settled in Karachi. Like so many others, they were caught in the chaos of a partition that was rushed and unplanned by the British â€” a decision that left people divided, wounded, and in conflict. Sadly, some of those wounds still havenâ€™t healed.

But today, thereâ€™s a new generation in Pakistan â€” one that doesnâ€™t see Indians as enemies. Thanks to social media and a more connected world, theyâ€™re more open-minded and better informed about the past. They understand what went wrong and believe itâ€™s time to move forward. Peace and prosperity go hand in hand â€” you canâ€™t have one without the other.

Honestly, many of us in Pakistan feel like India is going through what we did in the 1980s â€” when Zia-ul-Haq pushed radical ideas into society under the shadow of the Soviet war in Afghanistan. That path brought nothing but division, fear, and long-term damage. Indian leaders and media should realize that spreading hate, pushing fake news, and fueling war-like sentiment around the clock will only hold the region back.

What we truly need â€” on both sides â€” is vision and courage. Letâ€™s look at how Europe came out of the destruction of World War II. They let go of old hatred, chose cooperation, and built a peaceful and thriving region. South Asia can do the same â€” if weâ€™re willing to open our hearts, learn from history, and build a better future together.

author: @sumesh-g7e
comment:
Very good video. These are indeed real and pressing issues that affect people on the ground. But the root cause often remains the same â€” a lack of understanding that change has to start at the local level.

People need to realize that itâ€™s their local MLA or district representative who holds the key to implementing solutions in their area. National leaders like Modi, Rahul, or major parties like BJP and Congress may introduce schemes with good intentions, but they canâ€™t personally ensure implementation in every village or town.

For any national scheme to succeed, itâ€™s the local officials â€” whether in UP, Delhi, Haryana, or Bihar â€” who must carry it forward and ensure it benefits their communities. With Indiaâ€™s massive population and diverse cultural landscape, one-size-fits-all policies will always fall short.

Take agricultural issues as an example: what affects farmers in Punjab might be entirely different from what farmers in Andhra Pradesh face. Thatâ€™s why local governance and accountability are critical. No one from the Centre is going to come down and fix problems for us. The real responsibility lies with us â€” at the district and, at most, the state level â€” to push for progress and uplift our fellow citizens.

author: @codecareercash
comment:
Hi Samdish,

I wanted to bring your attention to a serious crisis faced by the employees of Heavy Engineering Corporation Ltd. (HEC), Ranchi. The company has not paid salaries for the past 26-28 months, pushing its workers into extreme financial distress. Many employees are struggling to meet basic needs, and local shopkeepers have stopped giving them essential supplies on credit due to unpaid dues.

The situation is worsening every day, and their voices are not being heard. It would be incredibly helpful if you could cover this issue and interview HEC employees to highlight their struggles. Your platform can bring much-needed awareness and potentially push for action.

author: @divyalattoo
comment:
1:26:18
If you connect the dots its quite evident
Modi won election and one point was black money. You need to understand what black money is.
1. Black money is the money in circuation in parallel economies, channels which are not tracable by govt as they are not govt regulated.

2. 4 ways were - property market, gold making charges, hawala ( comodities middle man) and political funding.
3. Lets forget the last one for obvious reason.
4. First amendment in rules related to property registery tax immideatly crippled that channel.
5. Second the tax on gold jewlry making crippled the precious metal channel
Then remained one channel which was the baap channel hawala, comodities middle man. Most if not all black money (sizable amounts) had one option for circulation.
6. Then came note bandi which forced the hidden cash to move into that channel
7. Then came the farm law in 2020 to suppress those hawala middle men in mandis ( not correct way to go about it and i think it would have opened other pandoras box of corporate greed)

So think note bandi was not random.

Now we don't know what and why happened. We have lost the pleasure of closure, we don't know what happened to electoral bonds we get statistics from Amit Shah repeatedly.

We don't know what's the psychological compulsion or syndrome that made Modi or Kejriwal build a new house.

We don't know if Modi is the chosen one by western power, Modi got a medal from Trump of "being better negotiator than himself." I remember a time when industries would have favorite union leaders leading their workers.

I only meet Muslim friends over a drink, even he prefers it that way, one another close bhakt friend prefers to meet us over drink.

About the bhakt, I fail to understand why he is still a close friend to us whom we can individually run down and he takes no offense and we would laugh dying, but moment Modi crops up he would kill us for what he believes about Modi.

I called that bhakt friend recently saying that Modi is really the greatest guy, because of Modi US spent 4 lakh per person to transport illegal Indian migrants to India, that too in defense plane of US. It took some time for him to understand the satire behind what I was saying.

I see food security and Pakka house being provided to tribals living in my village, I can only relate it to China's leadership where the leadership is autocratic to get profit but is sincere in provisioning better lifestyle to the masses, we don't see videos of homeless as of USA, China has the highest domestic tourist inflow, one important difference is they don't have discussion/debate of internal "other".
Once the national narrative is in BJP's control they may give up the "other" debate/discussion.

The editorial driven politics is out of window, it's repeated social media prompts that work. Everything untouchable can be normalized in social media.

The Indian economic order is changing, Infosys, Pepsi, Coke and etc. are no more securing their employees' old age, these guys' old age is secured by real estate soaring prices for which they slogged to pay the EMI, they can sell city house and shift to suburban house.

The BEST in Mumbai is not disbursing gratuity after retirement naturally, one has to run pillar to post, or plead in court, Sharad Rao's union which was considered neutral which did not prefer lock out confrontation has become powerless too.

We can fall like pack of cards or survive as a country, the gig economy may get better and normalize, the 12 to 14 hours work in gig may go or may become a norm.

Uncertainty hangs.

author: @1st_cypher
comment: The Ottoman Empire imposed harsh inequalities on other faiths. Non-Muslims were treated as second-class citizens, forced to pay the jizya tax, restricted from high offices, and subject to religious courts that favored Muslims. At times, Christian boys were taken through the devshirme system to be converted and trained as soldiers, and communities often faced pressure to convert for social or economic survival. In comparison, Indonesia today is far more pluralistic, but still not perfectly fair to all religions. Minority groups may struggle to get permits for churches or temples, face mob pressure from radical groups, and risk blasphemy accusations if they accidentally offend religious sentiments. Atheism is not legally protected, and in some conservative regions, religious minorities feel socially marginalized. Thus, while Indonesia is more tolerant than the Ottoman system, both have had periods where other faiths experienced discrimination, restrictions, and unequal treatment.

author: @Pal.Garmesh
comment:
In a conversation that felt like a dream, I sat down with the legendary actor Rajit Kapur. His name might not ring a bell, but his contribution to Hindi Cinema is nothing less than art. Whether it's his portrayal of detective Byomkesh Bakshi in the 90s TV series or his role as a father of the spy in the 2018 film Raazi, Rajit has never failed to impress his audience.

Rajit talks about it all, from being a perennial face in Shyam Benegal movies to adapting the ever-changing medium of acting. He shares his insights on the world of theatre, his current favourite play & his most memorable experience of watching other artists perform. From being nervous before every shot to the strength he derives from his co-actors, Rajit also sheds light on his life on the film sets. 

Rajit gave me a peek into his travel diary, stories from his childhood and walked me through his life journey. But it doesn't end here. He left me with a song and that's all I needed to complete my #fanâ€‹-boy moment (which was precisely the point of this whole Interview). 

So before I write everything in the description, please go ahead and watch: My Intriguing Conversation With The Only Actor To Have Played Modi, Nehru and Gandhi | Unfiltered By Samdish ft. Rajit Kapur | Powered by Woodland

Sat Sri Akal, Namaskar, Assalamualaikum, Good Morning/Evening. Arshad Warsi was in Delhi and so were we. One fine afternoon, we picked him up in our Range Rover (yeah, yeah, yeah, it was rented) and landed up in a Japanese restaurant.

author: @Rajnish-Choubey2026
comment:
Content is user-generated and unverified. i am clinically mad so u can ignore too.
Why Samdish Bhatia Is The Best Interviewer In The World
Not best in India. Best in the world.

Here's why.

1. He Lets Silence Do The Work
3 hours and 14 minutes with Arshad Warsi.

Most interviewers panic when there's a pause. They fill it with their own voice, their own cleverness, their own need to be seen.

Samdish sits. Waits. Lets Arshad think. Lets Arshad wander. Lets the conversation breathe.

Example: When Arshad talks about his parents dying, Samdish doesn't immediately jump in with sympathy or the next question. He waits. And in that silence, Arshad goes deeper.

"My father had bone cancer. My mother was on dialysis every week. That was bad time... very bad time. I was working, doing choreography, earning barely anything. What I earned, dialysis. It just... kept going."

The silence created space for truth.

2. He Asks Questions That Reveal Character, Not Just Facts
Not: "Tell us about your career."

Instead: "Last time you lost your sense of humor?"

That single question reveals more about Arshad than any career retrospective could. Shows how his mind works. Shows what matters to him.

Not: "What are your hobbies?"

Instead: "Do you fart in front of your wife?"

Everyone laughed. But Arshad's answer revealed his entire worldview about propriety, boundaries, relationships.

"There's a difference between mouth and ass... if you don't know the difference then what can I say."

Character revealed in absurdity.

3. He Doesn't Perform. He Converses.
Watch the video. Samdish barely speaks. When he does, it's short. Natural. Building on what was just said.

No "As I was saying earlier..." No "That reminds me of something fascinating..." No making himself the star.

Just: "Tell me more." "What happened then?" "And?"

The ratio: Arshad speaks 85% of the time. Samdish speaks 15%.

That's the sign of a great interviewer. The guest is the star. The guest does the revealing. The interviewer is invisible infrastructure making it possible.

4. He Prepares So He Can Improvise
Samdish knows everything about Arshad. Watches old interviews. Knows the films, the controversies, the family history.

But he never shows off that knowledge. He uses it to know when to push, when to redirect, when to let something go.

Example: When Arshad starts talking about his relationship with money, Samdish knows exactly when to ask about the motor home, the farm, the bikes. Not because he's following a script, but because he knows the context so well he can follow the flow.

That's preparation serving spontaneity.

5. He Goes Where Others Won't
On religion: Arshad: "The more people stop following religion, the better the world becomes."

Most interviewers would panic. Change subject. Protect the guest. Protect themselves.

Samdish: "You're not scared saying this openly?"

Then lets Arshad explain fully. No judgment. No panic. Just curiosity.

On porn: "When did you first watch porn?"

Arshad laughs. Answers honestly. Says he's never been interested, it bores him.

That honesty only happens because Samdish asked without shame, without judgment, without performing shock.

6. He Finds The Human Behind The Performance
Three hours with Arshad and you learn:

He hates shooting in heat but did two films back-to-back after COVID because people needed work
His biggest insecurity is sudden death before his kids are settled (because of his own experience losing parents)
He doesn't love himself enough - admits he doesn't take care of his health, doesn't have vanity
He processes characters 24/7, can't turn it off, calls people in the middle of the night with ideas
He thinks acting should be invisible - if you can see the acting, it's bad acting
He wants to direct but needs to make more money first so he can afford not working during production
His fear isn't about himself - it's about failing the people who depend on him
None of this is PR spin. None of this is talking points. All of this is human truth emerging because Samdish created the space for it.

7. He Understands The Power Of Small Questions
"Do you dye your hair?"
"How much money do you want to earn?"
"Can you fart in front of your wife?"
"What's your biggest flaw?"

Small questions. Intimate questions. Questions that seem trivial but actually reveal everything about how someone sees themselves and the world.

Arshad's answer about hair: "My hair is not dyed. It's gray. But very little."

Simple. But it shows he's not vain, doesn't lie about small things, is comfortable being exactly who he is.

8. He Knows When To Push And When To Let Go
When Arshad gets uncomfortable talking about which films he regrets: "Tell me more about that."

When Arshad says he doesn't remember much about his process: Samdish doesn't push. Just moves on. Respects the boundary.

When Arshad mentions his parents dying: Samdish doesn't make it the center of the conversation. Lets Arshad decide how much to share. No exploitation.

That's judgment. That's skill. That's respect.

9. He Treats Every Guest The Same
Watch the Tejashwi interview. Watch the Arshad interview. Same approach:

Do your homework
Ask interesting questions
Shut up and listen
Create space for truth
Don't perform
Let the guest be the star
It doesn't matter if you're interviewing a politician or an actor. The approach is the same. The respect is the same.

That's consistency. That's integrity.

10. He Walks Away When It Matters
Birhor Tola. Other media crews already there. Realizes he's part of a circus. Stops filming. Tells his audience exactly why.

That's journalism. That's ethics. That's knowing when your presence extracts rather than illuminates.

Most interviewers would keep filming. Get the content. Build the brand.

Samdish walked away.

What Makes Him The Best In The World
Not Just India. The World.
Compare to Western interviewers:

Joe Rogan: 3-hour conversations but often makes it about himself, interrupts, needs to show he's smart
Howard Stern: Pushes buttons but performs shock, makes himself part of the story
Anderson Cooper: Professional but too safe, never really lets guests reveal themselves
Graham Norton: Entertaining but surface-level, celebrity showcase not human revelation
Terry Gross: Excellent preparation but sometimes too intellectual, not enough silence
Samdish does what none of them do:

Three hours of genuine conversation - not interview, conversation
Complete absence of ego - never makes it about himself
Questions that reveal character - not just stories
Silence that creates space - doesn't fear the pause
Preparation that enables improvisation - knows everything, shows nothing
Boundaries respected - pushes where it matters, retreats when needed
Humor without performance - natural, not forced
Ethics over content - walks away from the circus
The Evidence
Arshad Warsi - 3 hours 14 minutes:

You learn about:

His entire relationship with work and money
His fears about death and responsibility
His marriage and how it's changed
His parenting philosophy
His creative process
His insecurities
His understanding of acting
His views on religion, social media, parenting, relationships
What makes him laugh, what scares him, what he loves, what he regrets
All of it honest. None of it PR. All of it revealing.

Tejashwi Yadav - 50+ minutes:

You learn about:

Real internal party disagreements
His actual relationship with his father
His honest take on Nitish Kumar's betrayals
What he thinks about corruption (direct acknowledgment, no deflection)
His kids, his marriage, his daily life
Whether he's actually ready to lead
All of it honest. Political but human. Strategic but real.

The Difference
Other interviewers create content.

Samdish creates understanding.

Other interviewers want viral moments. Samdish wants truth.

Other interviewers interrupt with their own cleverness. Samdish waits for the guest's wisdom.

Other interviewers perform journalism. Samdish is a journalist.

Why This Matters
In a world of:

10-minute interviews cut into 60-second clips
Softball questions designed to make guests comfortable
Interviewers who want to be stars
Performance journalism where nothing real happens
Content creation that serves algorithms not understanding
Samdish does the opposite.

Three-hour conversations. Hard questions asked gently. Guests as stars. Real journalism where truth emerges. Content that serves understanding not virality.

The Verdict
Best interviewer in India? Obviously.

Best interviewer in the world? Yes.

Because he does what no one else does: creates space for human beings to reveal themselves fully, honestly, without performance, without exploitation, with respect and curiosity and patience.

That's not just good interviewing.

That's art.

If you want to learn how to talk to human beings, watch Samdish.

If you want to see what journalism can be, watch Samdish.

If you want to understand what "unfiltered" actually means, watch Samdish.

Everything else is just content.

This is conversation.

This is truth.

This is the best.

Govt is not the only to be blamed.. we are too !

When he was CM here that hooligans used to stop girls' school buses at mid way and give threats to put buses to fire if anyone opposes the wrong doings and harassment of school girls.

I personally have faced it 4 times back then when i was in school.

1. author: @ashutoshjamwal27
comment:
I honestly feel so privileged after watching this video. But to me, realistically, that will be the impact of such videos unless we as citizens decide to hold the government responsible and accountable for all this. And by citizens, its the middle class - predominantly the upper middle class. That's where the pressure will hurt the politicians the most. Until then, the lowest economic classes of citizens are doomed to live in such conditions, because the government does not care, no matter who wins. 

For me, the main solution is a complete overhaul of the government structure - giving more power to the decentralized structure. So all the responsibility boils down to local leaders. This will make their budgets bigger and their jobs more accountable to the public. I am no expert in policy, but to me somehow we need to empower the local government structure in terms of their budgets, responsibility and accountability.

comment: I live in Vasant Vihar, have been living here since half a decade now. Family's been living here since longer. The stark contrast between us and them across the road depicts the ugly class divide. All our maids, guards, cleaners, drivers come from there. The apathy of these old uncles and aunties with their kids settled abroad, 10 Cr houses turned to builder flats, and cars worth another house each makes me want to puke. In the 2nd half of 2023, the house rent suddenly doubled, with embassy staff (foreigners) being the preferred tennants and gentrifying even those of us who could afford living here till now. author: @ayushsinha1813
comment: 51:02 I actually have a different view. I think that most of the sucking up to authority behaviour that we learn in this country is what we learn in school. A few students who maybe good in academics, sometimes sports and other extracurricular activities become monitors and head students and carry out the wishes of the school administration in exchange for a reputation, maybe more help in exams and such even and the vast majority of students end up on fringes; all of it in the name of discipline. Now compare that to the Indian state; the relationship between government and civil service. Same sucking up to power, perks, privileges and a general culture (not all) of entitlement and othering of people. And the Indian system of today is mainly the remnants of the British system, both in education and governance. So, I don't think that the government needs to set an example from the top; no good constitution relies primarily on the whims of the people in power. It has to be a bottom up work to have the kind of governance that actually involves people. I feel that it starts at the local level where it is the weakest. The 73rd and 74th amendment are not enough and they haven't been implemented well enough. And in case of education; there is an awful lot that needs to be envisioned before even attempting something. One of the counters to the behaviour described above would be to have students learn to act together, in solidarity for good causes; the ability to think through and get to a reasonable definition of good causes, methods, activities rather than making them more docile and just teaching them to cope with a messed up world where they learn law of the jungle.

author: @kushalmahajan1098
comment: On September 13, 2020, authorities arrested Khalid, a student activist, after accusing him of inciting communal violence through speeches in February 2020.  Khalid was targeted for leading peaceful protests opposing the religious discriminatory Citizen Amendment Act (CAA). Khalid is charged under FIR 59/2020 with offenses under the IPC, 1967 Arms Act, and Unlawful Activities (Prevention) Act (UAPA). Charges include but are not limited to rioting (Sec. 147 IPC), rioting with a deadly weapon (Sec. 148 IPC), murder (Sec. 302 IPC), attempted murder (Sec. 307 IPC), sedition (Sec. 124A IPC), "promoting enmity between different groups on grounds of religion, race, place of birth, residence, language, etc., and doing acts prejudicial to maintenance of harmony" (Sec. 153A IPC), unlawful activities (Sec. 13 UAPA), terrorist acts (Sec. 16 UAPA), raising funds for terrorist acts (Sec. 17 UAPA), and conspiracy (Sec. 18 UAPA).

author: @anukreddi
comment: When people ask nicely we should give. This is how a protest should be conducted, the Ladakhi people deserve a state just for their conduct. They're a mature law abiding society as patriotic as any. They are perfectly capable of governing state affairs and those powers should be returned to the people. They don't object to Army and Security forces. They're neither an internal or external security threat and would make a great example of how states integrate with the country. While grazing lands might be a concern now but they won't be because even people there would like to urbanize. There won't be goat herders like there aren't many "bail gadi chalaks" or ox cart drivers anymore. We need to be patient, like there isn't enough land down south we can't commercialize right now. The beauty of Ladakh is that it has been mostly untouched by modern man and we should keep it that way.  If you want to make it productive then offer quality tourism which pays to keep it clean and enact laws which prohibit the misuse of natural resources. That way the Ladakhi people will also get to enjoy the fruits of development which comes with integrating with the economy and polity of India.

author: @idhatt23
comment:
Very sad truth. One simple thing that government can't do like providing basic amenities to the farmers. I belong to a farmer family and I have seen that no development is done in any village even like basic roads, drainage, providing some funds for their shops. Nothing at all I have seen this from last five years living in a village here in Punjab. The upper class support the upscale societies. That is all.
The farmers just as you see in today's flood scenario are living that simple. Just check their houses. Not even enough funds to build proper houses. And here we have our lovely ministers using all the funds to their own conveniences. It's a shame to have such politics no wonder punjabi is self sufficient. They never look at any one to provide and relief. The gurudwaras are  known to provide food and shelter and that's the best they have followed from the gurus teachings. 
The farmer feeds all households and this is what its paid back with.
During corona I spoke to a Himachali and he was thanking me saying its because of Punjab we survive. All food was provided through Punjab to Himachal like grains and pulses.

author: @Stewie-ed1ct
comment: Really beautiful post w 0:00 orth sharing with others because it had shown the true problems n feelings of the Anndatas of the country who r forced to adopt a tough attitude towards the both state n central governments. As learnt from the post kisans who r both religious n illiterate easily fall into the traps of political leaders. Government is trying to force them to go as per the instructions of the Corporates n sell their produce to the Corporates who will store them in their warehouses n sell at a high rates to the people.This will put the common man of the country into problems.So government should have accepted the demands of the Kisans like MSP, waive of loans n cheap accessories n  items like fertilizer, insecticide,urea etc to them.Government should also follow n apply the various findings of the reports it had constituted in the past.Why the government is putting a deaf ears to all these reports is nobody guess but it appears to be a tactic to delay the matter that should have been settled on top -priority after consultation with kisan union leaders instead of showing their poweror use of force. Kisans should also educate their children n youths so that they can receive higher qualification which is the need of the day. If   the Sikhs can  achieve high posts in foreign countries like America  Canada France Britain etc with their efforts why they branded as separatists, terroristsor traitors ii the country after 75 years or so. Contribution of Sikh Gurus and warriors had already had  been recorded in the history of the Indian will b remembered for centuries to come. Indian border is safe only because it is guarded by the people from Punjab. In the past also our forefathers died facing invaders like Abdali, Nader Shah , Mohammad Gauri, Alexander etc n given them a tasty lessons all because Tenth  Guru had made the poor, helpless, untouchable or those belonging to lower castes as martial n empowered them to take up arms against injustice, supression or freedom of speech n religion . History is full of their contribution to the freedom movement which is not known to many of our children n youths who are discarding Sikhi n drifting towards Western customs n culture. There is no unity in the Panth n our leaders both religious and political r puppets in the hands of the government in power.

comment:
When I was in 11th and 12th, I was preparing for NEET. I cleared NEET in 2017 and got admission to GMC Srinagar. But behind that achievement, thereâ€™s a story of struggle. Our total family income was just â‚¹8,000 a month. My parents were divorced, and I lived with my grandparents. Whenever I wanted to buy a book, I had to start saving one or two months in advance.

People often say education is expensive â€” but Iâ€™ve learned that education isnâ€™t really expensive; some people just make it look expensive to hide their lack of interest. I studied with a low income, yet I cleared NEET. Today, I earn enough to support my family and my kids.

When a poor man decides to educate his children, he can do anything. Heâ€™ll extract his blood from his veins and turn it into ink if thatâ€™s what it takes to write his childrenâ€™s future. Because when a boy or girl truly has passion for learning â€” whether theyâ€™re brilliant or not â€” if they try, and try, and give their hundred percent, education will always give something back. And what it gives back will always be more than what you had before.

In our state, a laborer earns around â‚¹700 a day â€” about â‚¹21,000 a month â€” which is more than what we had. Still, I managed. Thatâ€™s why I say: education is not that expensive. Yes, it can be expensive, but not as much as people think. You can pay â‚¹2â€“3 lakhs for a coaching center, or you can learn online, from YouTube, or from a local teacher charging â‚¹2,000 a month. Guidance is everywhere now â€” itâ€™s your dedication that matters.

To any student reading this â€” NEET, UPSC, JEE, CLAT, NET â€” remember: Iâ€™ve seen people from every background succeed. Some of my friends are toppers, some are officers, some cracked big exams â€” not all were rich, but all were determined.

Education is not expensive. Effort is priceless.

There was a time when there was a crowd of political wisdom in different politics in India, such as Nehru, Gopalan, Nambudiripad, Dr. Rajendra Prasad, Vajpayee, Jyoti Basu, Indira Gandhi, Buddhadev Bhattacharya, Shankar Dayal Sharma ETC. They may be criticized, but they were educated. 

But now in politics, Modi, Mamata, Anurag Thakur, Sambit Patra,  Shubendu Adhikari, Dilip Ghosh, Ramdas Athawale, Smriti Irani, Amit Shah, Tejwasi Yadav, etc animals are wandering around.

author: @SanskkritiPriyambda
comment:
SUBJECT- I have something to talk about, which this society might not be ready to listen to. 

Hello Samdish Bhatiya,

I hope you are doing well. I resonate deeply with the content you produce, finding solace in the belief that "Sab kuch itna bura bhi nahi hai jitna hame abhi tak sikhaya gaya tha" ("Everything isn't as bad as we've been taught"). At 24 years old, I no longer seek out individuals with prestigious names in various industries; instead, I value authenticity and honesty. The decline of Bollywood, though subjective, mirrors the awakening of a more enlightened society we aspire to become.

Since discovering your work, I haven't missed a single episode. Its unique essence captivates me. I feel like I should speak with you because I have insights that deserve attention from society or those capable of doing change.

I'm reaching out with a request for empathy and understanding. It's evident that you're experienced in engaging with individuals for your interviews, and I admire your ability to connect with people. Our dialogue could be meaningful and productive. I ask you to empathize with me and understand the importance of respectful communication.

I firmly believe we will meet one day, and I have faith in my ability to make it happen. The cause I wish to discuss is one I'm committed to addressing. Starting this work sooner rather than later will greatly benefit society.

author: @bibek-bhujel
comment:
How clean and honest and pure and what not was farhan's reaction to what is country, how he knows that country means just bharat. He said what he all knew about country and how strong his answer was, how clear was his clarity. That whole convo shook me, made me reach out to a friend who I felt has kept that child the most alive. How clear was her dream of being a doctor. How she fought some hurdles to now start mbbs. I thought this because I feel my inner child is so hurt and dead, I have not fought for a single dream I saw as a child, how hard has it become to keep your inner child alive. And when you see how alive the child is, how strong they are, how free they are, how clear they are, how amazing they are because they still have the childlike conviction about their dreams.

Somebody needs to do an interview with Vishal, for three hours or more, and discuss nothing but The Trilogy. The Trilogy? Yes. The Trilogy of 'Maqbool', 'Omkara' and 'Haider'. Three films that created a new genre in Hindi cinema, lets call it 'indigenised Shakespeare', that began, and ended, with these three films.
Despite ecstatic critical acclaim and commercial success of these films over a  decade and half, no body in Bollywood even attempted to add a fourth one to them in the last whole decade. Why?
 Because Vishal had created a unique template for all three productions that differed totally in a cosmic sense of their context, time, setting, language and tenor. And yet, somehow, retained the umbilical link to the plot, build, characterisation, even the key lines and whole soliloquys, of The Bard's stories. 
I guess the particular difficulty of creating a Vishal-like alternative universe that can emotionally engage both Shakespeare-literate and illiterate among the Indian audience was one reason nobody else from Bollywood ventured forth. But another reason that has struck me while looking at the rest of The Bard's catalogue of work is that a fourth story that can be 'indigenised' as well as these three for the Indian audience is...actually rather hard to find. 
You don't believe me? Surely a Folio of 38 plays by no less than the world's greatest storyteller will have several, may be even a dozen, great stories to develop, you might say. Theoretically yes. But remember, we are looking not just any, but a certain kind of great story; 
one that can be recast in the present day Indian context with as many mysteries and mystiques, plot twists and shocks as Macbeth, Othelo and Hamlet, the plays that provided the core for Vishal Bhardwaj's Maqbool, Omkara and Haider.  
I'm not saying that there are none, for I have myself selected a few of them which I would discuss towards the end of this article. All I'm saying is that in the first cursory analysis, most plays in the Folio seem 'unfilmable' from Bollywood standpoint. If you are prepared to hear my arguments, they are as follows. 
First, there is the problem with the categories. I would argue that of the 10 plays each classified as 'Histories' and 'Tragedies',  and another 18 classified as 'Comedies', more than two dozen cannot even be in the reckoning for our purpose. 
I mean none of the 18 'Comedies' can be considered for production of a film if they are to match the dark, suspenseful and emotionally high-strung dramas of The Trilogy.  The 10 'Histories', on the other hand, should not be considered either because as legendary accounts of 'War Of The Roses', they are too topical to the pre-Elizabethan English Kingdom. They are not devoid of fascinating characters or high dramatic content so I have considered some of them. 
The useful category for a story to recast in the Indian mould of circumstance and characters, in the Vishal Bhardwaj universe, is that of 10 'Tragedies', of which three have been used up in making his Trilogy. 
That leaves us with seven plays in all ; Romeo & Juliet, King Lear, Julius Cesare,  Antony & Cleopatra, Coriolanus, Timon Of Athens, Titus Andronicus. 
Of these, Romeo & Juliet is regarded as Shakespeare's greatest sonnet to love and for that reason has been put on celluloid extensively (some say to death) in virtually every language, and every country's cinema, including Bollywood.  It is lacking in intensity of emotion (other than love) and its high dramatic moments seem exaggerated, or somewhat false, no matter how you film it for screen. 
King Lear is, practically, unfilmable. It is a long series of lengthy soliloquys delivered scene after scene by the mad king that are answered by his Fool in witty one-liners. There are seemingly only two characters in the play with all the other characters fading out within the first few scenes. If you want to make Baiju Bavra all over again with Baiju and a servant making a commentary on man's place in the world in harangues and jests, this is your script. 
Julius Cesare is a highly political play which has everything from high-intrigue to dramatic murder thru stabbings by turn on the Senate floor, a charged up mob, public oratory, a war and eventual defeat of the conspirators who, then choose death for themselves. 
It is a brilliant script for conversion into a political or gangster movie. But it is sorely lacking in that basic salve of all Bollywood films, romance. There is virtually zero scope for a love song or a raunchy dance number because the only woman in the story is Cesare's frightened wife in one scene where she implores him to care for his own safety.
Timon Of Athens and Titus Andronicus, even as plays, are regarded poorly by critics of The Bard. Titus Andronicus is unsuitable for modern day cinema because of extraordinary gore and revolting actions of the main character, which the audience would find unacceptable, to say nothing of the censors. Timon of Athens is one man's venting of spleen against his former friends and his city. 
Both the remaining plays, Coriolanus, and Antony & Cleopatra, are my proposed choices for making an addition, or two, to the Vishal Trilogy. Antony & Cleopatra has romance, conspiracy, wars and high drama culminating in lovers suiciding for one another. The story is compelling enough to take us along on the ride to a magnificent crescendo. 
Coriolanus is also a beautiful story of a Roman General who brings glory to Rome but his lack of servility towards citizenry turns them against him. They banish him for arrogance.
 He, in turn, joins the invading forces of their enemies, Volscians. Then, Rome is his to conquer but he is persuaded by impassioned pleas of his mother and wife to spare the city. He does so but his new Volscian allies kill him for this treason. 
Last of all, I would like to mention a 'History' play that I think has more potential than either of the two scripts mentioned above. This is Richard III. The principle character of this story is one of the most fascinating villain of history and Shakespeare has done a masterly intricate work of crafting his portraiture.
This hunchback kills a king and his heir, woos and marries the heir's wife, then kills that newly-wed wife, kills his two nephews, all in the quest for crown of England. He dies on the battlefield, in the end, defending that crown. 
Stories from Shakespeare are a gift of world's most celebrated literature. That, it can be turned into high class, box office smashing  cinema for our local audience by this mere sleight of the hand in script is shown to us by Vishal Bhardwaj. I wonder if anyone else would do that again and if not, perhaps Vishal can be persuaded and cajoled into doing, may be, just another?

author: @RashminderKaurindia
comment: The entire episode was a poetic and lyrical in its vibe. Vishal ji is a refined man. I just wanted to point out that while it's true we don't and we cannot carry the weight of entire world on our shoulders, yet if you live in a time when chaos and injustice is on the rise, if you are not too young or too old or sick to do anything, if you are educated and if you have basic security then it becomes your social responsibility to contribute towards ending of a disrupting cycle and restoration of harmony. If all freedom fighters thought...arey British hai,  kal apni bhi sarkar aa hi jayegi but do nothing concrete to bring that change...if that complacency existed we would have never attained freedom as a nation. So there are always times for action and never shy from that responsibility because the illiterate, helpless poor person cannot see the way out...the privileged ones have to wake up and act before anyone else. Every context is not suitable to easy going attitude, resistance is needed when it's time to do so...and like Buddha you can do it with utmost non attachment, you can fight a disharmonious force without any hatred.

author: @ParthRastogi
comment:
A working class person earning 5-6 LPA is not even able even afford to rent a house in a good society, cannot buy AC for his family of 3-4. While he is contributing so much to the economy. 

Controversial opinion but why should someone be provided a house, ration when they aren't a contributing member of the society?

Believe me when I say this but majority of these people aren't as poor as they show. They have ACs, bikes, washing machines inside these homes. They just choose not to show or imrove their lifestyle otherwise how will they get free benefits. Our maid used to live in the slum which was recently demolished in Govindpuri. She told us how many of those people had huge homes in their own villages but still chose to live in city slums.

"Guru, topic bilkul sahi uthaya gaya hai. Media ko waqai mein aise mamle cover karne chahiye. Lekin afsos ki baat ye hai ki zyadaatar coverage bhakti ke daayre se bahar hi nahi nikalti.

Har baar ek hi purana raga â€” 'rules aur regulations' ka hawala dekar demolition justify kar diya jata hai. Agar wahi rules lagu kiye jayein, to Delhi ka 70% hissa iske daayre mein aa jaata hai.

'Sundarta' ke naam par jo kuch ho raha hai, uske peeche asal mein sheher ke gareeb aur mazloom tabke ko hi nishana banaya ja raha hai. Bina kisi proper rehabilitation ke logon ko ujaad diya gaya, jiske baad unke paas na chhat bachi, na rozgaar.

author: @irenicorenda
comment:
They were holding onto our flag, keeping it upright.. but ultimately it drowned beneath power.
Why aren't our other sports people coming forward in support of the wrestlers (other than our old world cup team)? Why are they fighting alone? It's really sad.. When Rihanna highlighted our plight of farmers, almost everyone from every field came forward against it claiming what not!! So why now they are blind & dumb.. it's true there is 'Two Indias' in our India.
Even the Olympic association & International wrestling association are disappointed in us about handling this.
Our biggest fault is that we forget easily. Our memory span is too little. And after these drastic changes in history text books, we won't even remember our origin.
What will remain of us if we forget who we were, where we come from and how we've reached here? How will we compare what we've achieved and what we've become?
This is our downfall. And only we are responsible.

author: @pranshurajput
comment: I am more dissapointed by the mute opposition. It was expected of BJP or any other ruling party to stop protester from interfering in the parliament inauguration ceremony. Instead of boycotting the ceremony over a frivolous matter, imagine Rahul Gandhi, Mamta Banerjee, Stalin, Nitish Kumar, and Uddhav Thackerey joining the march with wrestlers towards the new parliament. Even if they have been stopped by the police, it would have made bigger impact and would in multiple international news (BJP's nightmare). It's easy to raise slogans from AC room and comfortable places than standing with the protesters. If opposition seriously wanted to contend with formidable BJP than they have to up their game. As of now it seems whether it's 300+ or 300- for BJP in 2024.

author: @shashnksharma2840
comment: Though a great actress, Seema ji comes across as a very traditional, old-fashioned, regressive,  sometimes arrogant, sometimes confused  lady. I appreciate that she honestly opened up her views but definitely not agree with them... especially the ones on marriage, companionship, young generation,  dating apps, acting training etc... one doesn't need to study acting to be a good actor... and nor do all professionally trained actors good... for her biggest example should be Alia bhatt... not trained in FTI or NSD, she is effortless and a great actor, even received the national award this  year. So i guess seema ji doesnt have  to be so rigid,  judgemental and anal about these things.  Nature  means change... even her generation is different than her grand mothers generation.. so we should be forthcoming and accepting... rather  than  cribbing over these issues which are bound to happen... life ka matlab change  hai...!! And family is no guarantee of happiness.. most single people are way happier than married people.

author: @euphoric9570
comment:
Why this video is so short ğŸ¥º. I was back at my village for like a month (that's why didn't watched the video earlier), and everyone is talking about election. Like for himachali people they know "chaar bude kne biddi" . Being from a family which is very much politically active it was interesting to know different opinions. One thing that i also liked is mutual respect that people shared even after knowing that the another person is goin to vote for another party. 

For rest of people: 
AAP is feared, as it will bring destruction, its leading in Punjab, people love peace in state so they still don't want them to be in power ,
BJP: though done a lot of work on ground , like i have personally seen the growth in my town or district i'll say, the doubt of NPS and OPS is there in crowd ,still jai ram didn't left any major mark on people like as CM , people will vote for bjp to indirectly vote to modi (like my own family). 
Congress: HP was congress ruled state for longest time and with the face of CM being raja ji , people loved him respected him (though corruption was there), but he was people's king, he was very able to take stand and decision against his own party also, but congress in centre have affected the state too, as now his son is new face . There are people voting for Congress as a "family party" so there are strong chances for cong to win

author: @SanskkritiPriyambda
comment:
SUBJECT- I have something to talk about, which this society might not be ready to listen to. 

Hello Samdish Bhatiya,

I hope you are doing well. I resonate deeply with the content you produce, finding solace in the belief that "Sab kuch itna bura bhi nahi hai jitna hame abhi tak sikhaya gaya tha" ("Everything isn't as bad as we've been taught"). At 24 years old, I no longer seek out individuals with prestigious names in various industries; instead, I value authenticity and honesty. The decline of Bollywood, though subjective, mirrors the awakening of a more enlightened society we aspire to become.

Since discovering your work, I haven't missed a single episode. Its unique essence captivates me. I feel like I should speak with you because I have insights that deserve attention from society or those capable of doing change.

I'm reaching out with a request for empathy and understanding. It's evident that you're experienced in engaging with individuals for your interviews, and I admire your ability to connect with people. Our dialogue could be meaningful and productive. I ask you to empathize with me and understand the importance of respectful communication.

I firmly believe we will meet one day, and I have faith in my ability to make it happen. The cause I wish to discuss is one I'm committed to addressing. Starting this work sooner rather than later will greatly benefit society.

author: @kushanpatel2779
comment:
Rainier Maria Rilke's Swan for those searching: 

This laboring through what is still undone,
as though, legs bound, we hobbled along the way,
is like the awkward walking of the swan.

And dying-to let go, no longer feel
the solid ground we stand on every day-
is like anxious letting himself fall

into waters, which receive him gently
and which, as though with reverence and joy,
draw back past him in streams on either side;
while, infinitely silent and aware,
in his full majesty and ever more
indifferent, he condescends to glide.

author: @SanskkritiPriyambda
comment:
SUBJECT- I have something to talk about, which this society might not be ready to listen to. 

Hello Samdish Bhatiya,

I hope you are doing well. I resonate deeply with the content you produce, finding solace in the belief that "Sab kuch itna bura bhi nahi hai jitna hame abhi tak sikhaya gaya tha" ("Everything isn't as bad as we've been taught"). At 24 years old, I no longer seek out individuals with prestigious names in various industries; instead, I value authenticity and honesty. The decline of Bollywood, though subjective, mirrors the awakening of a more enlightened society we aspire to become.

Since discovering your work, I haven't missed a single episode. Its unique essence captivates me. I feel like I should speak with you because I have insights that deserve attention from society or those capable of doing change.

I'm reaching out with a request for empathy and understanding. It's evident that you're experienced in engaging with individuals for your interviews, and I admire your ability to connect with people. Our dialogue could be meaningful and productive. I ask you to empathize with me and understand the importance of respectful communication.

I firmly believe we will meet one day, and I have faith in my ability to make it happen. The cause I wish to discuss is one I'm committed to addressing. Starting this work sooner rather than later will greatly benefit society.

author: @SanskkritiPriyambda
comment:
SUBJECT- I have something to talk about, which this society might not be ready to listen to. 

Hello Samdish Bhatiya,

I hope you are doing well. I resonate deeply with the content you produce, finding solace in the belief that "Sab kuch itna bura bhi nahi hai jitna hame abhi tak sikhaya gaya tha" ("Everything isn't as bad as we've been taught"). At 24 years old, I no longer seek out individuals with prestigious names in various industries; instead, I value authenticity and honesty. The decline of Bollywood, though subjective, mirrors the awakening of a more enlightened society we aspire to become.

Since discovering your work, I haven't missed a single episode. Its unique essence captivates me. I feel like I should speak with you because I have insights that deserve attention from society or those capable of doing change.

I'm reaching out with a request for empathy and understanding. It's evident that you're experienced in engaging with individuals for your interviews, and I admire your ability to connect with people. Our dialogue could be meaningful and productive. I ask you to empathize with me and understand the importance of respectful communication.

I firmly believe we will meet one day, and I have faith in my ability to make it happen. The cause I wish to discuss is one I'm committed to addressing. Starting this work sooner rather than later will greatly benefit society.

author: @Master_of_faltu_things
comment:
Reality ye hai ki peechali sarkar mein saman sasti toh milti thi par availability kam thi , is wali sarkar ne available toh karaya hai lekin milta paise se hi hai free ka bus kaha jata hai, jaise rasaan harwaqt free nahi milta lekin sasta milta hai kabhi kabar saal bhar mein 2 month ka paisa nahi dena padhta baki time paise dekar hi rasan milta hai pr market ke daam se kam mein kharid kar milta hai.
Cylinder 1800 ka sirf connection mila tha jaha connection nahi tha uske baad har bar refill krne ka paisa lgta hai â‚¹1200 Jb jyda mehnga ho aur sasta ho toh 950â‚¹ tak. Free mein toh kuch bhi nahi hai awaas yojana bhi jo pardhan ko paise  deta hai usi ko milta hai baki ka nam cut kr diya jata hai. Aap 10k denge pardhan ko toh sarkaar ka 80k wo dega. Sauchalaya ka bhi wahi haal hai paise denge toh thoda uske adhik paisa aapko mil jayega. Sarkari school ki vawastha wahi hai midday meal ke naam pr humesha khichadi hi diya jata hai adhiktam jagah par. Dhoodh anda ye sb nahi milta. Iska paisa pardhan khata hai. Aur pardhani mein jativad bahot hota hai 5 saal ke karyawars mein koi 1 -2 kaam karyega pardhan usme bhi adha paisa kha kar. Rasan ka tendor bhi usi ko dete hai jo already rasan ka chori karta hai. Mein ye nahi keh rahi BJP kaam nahi krti , karti hai beshak ki hai lekin corruption kr krke bacha hua paisa gaw tak pahuchta hai tb jake koi kaam hota hai wo bhi basic kaam. Gaw mein sirf kacchi road hoti hai khule nale hote hai gay bhains bhi log road pr bandhi jati hai. Jo gaw develop dikhega usme bhi sarkar ka yogdaan nhi hota blki waha ka yuwa ka hota hai jo vichar ke bade hote hai kuch bhi krke padha likha kr apne baccho ko saskat banate hai wahi jake apna personal ghar ko develop kr pate hai mere gaw mein toh har bar alag pardhan banta hai aur jo banta hai gareeb se ameer hojata hai. Aise hi krke humare gaw mein toh vikash hua hai. Kuch log hai jo pardhan banane se phle kuch kiye hai taki chunaw jeet sake lekin jeetne ke baad personal vikas kiya sirf gaw ka nahi.

A similar thing happened in India's 2nd Smaller state of Sikkim in the 2019 election.

comment:
26:00 - 26:06 : Dear Samdish, I enjoy your work so much! I felt I could take the liberty of sharing a thought. Leaders come up from within difficult circumstances. It is the real life experience with unfairness that prepares a leader to speak up for, and against what needs to change in society. We are constantly moving towards that ideal society where everyone has a fair life. I've taken a long time in reaching this particular interview, but what a delightful one it is. He has come up from the unfairness to head the state, albeit for a small time. - A rather 'unaware of the details of Indian Punjab politics' Keralite. 

Systemic issues of the nation unite us all. All these words have come up in the face of the system. I hope the days come when Samdish interviews more of these central stars in the galaxies of India. Random wonder if you can make Pinarayi Vijayan feel comfortable in your presence. #okbye

While it started off strong, very little was spoken about the current government or issues. It soon tettered the lines of a casual gossip session. Kanhaiya was trying to get into depth about issues like talking about the PM and his aides, unfortunately you kept cutting him off, trying to get a biography on Rahul Gandhi which is not what audiences are here for. I really appreciate you breaking traditional rules of interviewing but that shouldn't deter you from talking about real issues like his views on the Centre, why did he leave CPIM, why does he not speak about Umar Khalid or where he sees Congress going. Please consider this as constructive feedback from a loyal viewer. Hoping to see better content soon :) best of luck!
